<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-05-15T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-05-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="767" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d767">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 815.51/337.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">
                                <gloss type="from">Wm. C. Sheldon and Company, Bankers</gloss>, to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-05-15">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 15, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>My dear Mr. Secretary: It gives me great pleasure to introduce herewith
                            Mr. Sol Wexler, Vice President of the Whitney-Central National Bank of
                            New Orleans, who is associated with us in the loan to Honduras. The
                            Whitney-Central National Bank is proposing to advance to Honduras
                            $500,000, and Mr. Wexler is anxious to submit the papers to you.</p>
                        <p>Thanking you for any courtesies you may extend to Mr. Wexler, I am
                            [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">George R. Sheldon.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Note.</hi>—Mr. Wexler called at the Department
                                on May 17 and spoke with Mr. Doyle and Mr. Wright.</p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>